                 Philadelphia Clerk of Quarter Sessions

                 Mission
                 The Clerk of Quarter Sessions serves the Criminal Courts of Common
   Pleas and Municipal Courts, as well as the Juvenile Division of Family
   Court.  It records, indexes and files all bills of information and
   transcripts of Municipal Court.  The department's clerks also post to
   dockets; take bail imposed by judges; enter orders for judgements upon
   bail forfeitures; issue bench warrants; collect fines and cost imposed
   by the courts; record on bills of information or criminal transcripts
   the decisions of the courts; issue commitments or discharges for
   defendants; and, when necessary, answer numerous inquiries from
   prisoners, attorneys, and judges.

   In serving the Juvenile Division of Family Court, the Clerk of Quarter
   Sessions handles all matters relative to court case files, including
   sending subpoenas to witnesses and notifying attorneys of case dates
   and activities.

   Frequently Asked Questions
   1. Where is Bail posted?
   Cash bail can be posted 24 hours a day, seven days a week, including
   holidays, at the Police Administration Building, 8th and Race Streets
   (215-686-1558 or 1559).  Bail is accepted Monday through Friday, from
   8:45 a.m. to 4:30 p.m., at the Criminal Justice Center, Payment Center,
   1301 Filbert Street.

   2. When and where are Bail Refunds obtained?
   Refunds are available 31 days following final disposition at the
   Payment Center, 1301 Filbert Street.  Hours are 8:45 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.,
   Monday through Friday.

   3. Where are Fines and Costs paid?
   Payments for all criminal cases are payable at the Payment Center
   Monday through Friday, from 8:45 a.m. to 4:45 p.m.

   4. Where can official copies of disposed cases be obtained?
   Official copies of disposed records are available at the Information
   Counter, Room 310, Criminal Justice Center, and can be reproduced at
   .25 cents per page.  Certified copies are $12.50.

   5. Can the public view any disposed records?
   Yes. Common Pleas Court (1988-1998) and Municipal Court disposed files
   (1990-1998) are housed in the file complex, Room 310, Criminal Justice
   Center.  Older files are maintained at the Record Storage Center.
   There is a two to three week waiting period

